[SourceTitle "S&S: The Magnus Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-magnus-sicilian/course/30136, variation/5395571"]

1. e4 c5 {Hello and Welcome to 'Short and Sweet: The Magnus Sicilian'! This 
'Short and Sweet' opening course provides you with an overview of the Sicilian, 
choosing lines based on World Champion Magnus Carlsen's repertoire. In the 
Sicilian Black immediately breaks the symmetry on move one, making it an ideal 
weapon to unbalance the game and play for a win. In the main lines of the 
Sveshnikov Black frequently sacrifices material to drum up an attack on the 
white king, which is fun to play and tricky for White to handle. If you are 
looking for an active and ambitious opening for Black, this is the right one for 
you. As of today (Nov 11, 2019) Magnus Carlsen has not lost a single game with 
the Siclian in Classical time control games since 2011! Admittedly, he did not 
play it that frequently between 2011 and 2018, but still a very impressive run. 
I am mentioning non-losing streaks, but what about wins? Magnus has won many 
attractive games with the Sicilian, often going all out for an attack on the 
king. I hope you enjoy this overview of the Sicilian, played like Magnus does 
it!} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d3 {White goes for a King's Indian Attack with g3 next. This 
way to play is much more interesting for White after 2... e6, as this limits 
Black's possible set-ups. Now we have a very convenient choice.} g6 {[%cal 
Bf8g7,Gg7d4,Bd7d6,Be7e5]} ({I think that the Botvinnik set-up with a later ...e5 
is excellent against the KIA. However, here you may also play} 3... Nf6 {and 
4... d5, which will very likely transpose into a line that is checked in the 
main course via 2. g3 d5 3. d3 Nc6 4. Nd2 Nf6.}) 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 d6 6. O-O e5 
{[%cal Ge5d4,Gc5d4,Gc6d4,Gg7d4,Bg8e7,Be8g8] We have completed the Botvinnik 
formation with ...c5 and ...e5. From here it is difficult to analyze on a 
move-by-move basis because White has so many different move orders available. 
For me the only set-up by White worth checking is a quick c3, a3, b4 push on the 
queenside. If White plays moves like Nbd2, Re1, a4 we will complete our standard 
set-up with ...Nge7,...O-O, ...h6, ...Be6 and ...Qd7. We are ready to play ...d5 
or ...f5 while it is unclear what White is playing for. Often the knight on f3 
goes to h4 or some other square to reach f4, but this is not dangerous. Against 
f4 we are well equipped to play ...d5, possibly after taking on f4 first. I will 
show one example of this type of play to illustrate ideas; the main course has 
more on this line.} 7. c3 ({As mentioned, I regard a quick c3/a3/b4 push as the 
only interesting idea for White. One thing to mention is that} 7. Nc3 {is also 
possible, but this we examine as part of the closed Sicilian via 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. 
g3 etc.}) Nge7 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gd6d5]} 8. a3 O-O ({This is important. We should not 
stop b4 with} 8... a5 {, as after} 9. a4 $1 {White gains useful control over the 
weakened squares on the queenside.}) 9. b4 a6 {[%cal Ga6b5][%csl Gb5]} 10. Nbd2 
h6 {[%cal Bc8e6,Bf7f5] This is the main move, preparing ...Be6. Now we have 
reached a rather slow-paced position with flexible move orders. Black's main 
idea is to play for ...f5 later, gaining space on the kingside.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Magnus Sicilian"]
[Site "S&S: The Magnus Sicilian"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model game: Svidler, Peter"]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus, Grenke Chess Classic 2019"]
[Result "0-1"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The Magnus Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-magnus-sicilian/course/30136, variation/5390881"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 e5 {Magnus is quick to adopt the Botvinnik set-up. 
It's a very solid way to play. Very little can go wrong for Black. We control 
the center and get our pieces out.} 4. Bc4 Be7 5. d3 d6 6. Nd2 Nf6 7. Nf1 Nd7 $1 
{A typical idea. The knight is coming around to the queenside, where it can 
harass the Bishop on c4, while also freeing up the kingside for a potential 
...f5 break. In some lines Black can also carry out ... Bg5.} 8. Nd5 (8. Ne3 Nb6 
9. O-O O-O 10. Ncd5 Bg5 {would be a very typical continuation. Black always has 
the possibility of taking on e3, eroding White's control over d5.}) Nb6 9. Nxb6 
axb6 10. c3 O-O 11. Ne3 (11. f4 {This is a bit loosening. The problem is that 
White's king is still stuck in the centre.} 11... b5 $5 ({The solid} 11... Be6 
{would no doubt have been preferred by Magnus. He always seems to love to play 
by position.} 12. f5 d5 $1 {is fun!} 13. fxe6 (13. Bb3 c4 {with the same idea.}) 
13... dxc4 $17) 12. Bxb5 f5 {Is a sharp and interesting idea, trying to quickly 
open the centre before White has completed his development.}) Bg5 {Black is very 
solid here and is very close to equalising completely. Again, this is a typical 
manoeuvre, exchanging some pieces and freeing up Black's position even more. We 
can think about putting the king on h8 and playing for the ...f5 break.} 12. O-O 
Kh8 {The ambitious try for Black.} ({There is the solid alternative} 12... Bxe3 
13. Bxe3 Be6 {This is possible, but less interesting than playing for ...f5 as 
in the game.}) 13. a3 (13. Nd5 {is the critical move that is analyzed in the 
theoretical section of the main course.}) f5 $1 {Black has carried out the 
desired break. Now the f8-rook can breathe on the half-open file, and Black's 
position is very easy to play.} 14. Nxf5 ({White could 'hang tough' with} 14. f3 
{but then a nice and straightforward way to play would be to pursue our policy 
of exchanges with} Bxe3+ 15. Bxe3 f4 $1 16. Bf2 Bd7 {and then eventually Black 
can continue with his play on the kingside, perhaps even a pawn storm with 
...g5-g4 etc. (Alternatively, piece play with .. .Qg5 and ...Rf6-g6 isn't bad 
either.) It looks like the kind of position where Alpha Zero is coming up with 
some powerful attacking plan, and as we know this is the direction that Magnus 
has been following of late.}) Bxc1 15. Rxc1 Bxf5 16. exf5 d5 {Building a very 
powerful centre.} 17. Ba2 Rxf5 18. Qg4 Rf6 19. f4 $2 {Trying desperately to get 
out of the typical Magnus vice-like grip that he seems to have inflicted on the 
position, but this only seems to accelerate White's fate.} (19. Rce1 Qd6 {and 
Black has something of a bind on the dark squares.}) exf4 20. Qg5 Qf8 21. Qxd5 
Rd8 22. Qf3 Ne5 23. Qe4 Ng4 (23... Re8 24. d4 Ng4 {was a reasonable alternative. 
Once again, the knight heads for e3.}) 24. Rce1 Ne3 25. Rf2 Re8 26. Qxb7 g5 $1 
{Again, very much in Alpha Zero style, going for a direct attack. The bishop on 
a2 is a particularly miserable piece (especially when you compare it with the 
dominant black knight on e3) and the computers already give Black a decisive 
edge here.} 27. Rfe2 (27. Qf3 g4 {and White is gradually being deprived of 
oxygen.} 28. Qe2 f3 $1 {with a crushing attack.}) g4 28. Rf2 ({It's difficult to 
give White any good advice. Also losing was} 28. d4 f3 29. Rf2 Re7 30. Qa6 Nxg2 
{When Black powers through.}) Qh6 29. Qc7 Ref8 30. h3 gxh3 31. g3 fxg3 32. Rxf6 
{True to his sportsmanslike ethos, Svidler allows a pretty mate on the board.} 
h2+ 33. Kh1 g2# 0-1

[Event "Short & Sweet: The Magnus Sicilian"]
[Site "S&S: The Magnus Sicilian"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model game: Cheparinov, Ivan"]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus, Wijk aan Zee 2005"]
[Result "0-1"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The Magnus Sicilian"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-magnus-sicilian/course/30136, variation/5413008"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 
b5 9. Bxf6 gxf6 {The dynamic recapture, and the only move.} (9... Qxf6 10. Nd5 
Qd8 11. c4 $1 ({Instead} 11. Bxb5 {is also terrible for Black.}) 11... b4 12. 
Qa4 Bd7 13. Nb5 $1 {Ouch!} axb5 14. Qxa8 Qxa8 15. Nc7+ {and White wins.}) 10. 
Nd5 Bg7 11. Bd3 Ne7 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 13. c4 (13. O-O {is the main alternative, 
although this often transposes to the move played in the game.} O-O 14. c4 f5 $1 
{with active counter-play for Black, as examined in the theoretical section.}) 
f5 $1 (13... bxc4 14. Nxc4 {and some sort of position where White imposes a bind 
with Ne3-d5, or Ne3-f5, is something we should definitely avoid. Therefore it's 
a good idea to play our dynamic ...f5 break as early as possible.}) 14. O-O O-O 
15. cxb5 $6 {This line gives Black good play without any particular problems to 
solve.} ({There are at least two meaty alternatives for White here, one of which 
is} 15. Qh5 Rb8 16. exf5 e4 17. Rae1 Bb7 {And here White has a wide choice, as 
examined in the theoretical section.}) (15. Qf3 d5 16. cxd5 fxe4 17. Bxe4 Rb8 
{And Black obtains enough compensation, as examined in the course. For both of 
these lines I refer you to the *11. Bd3 chapter*.}) d5 $1 {This is the idea. 
Black forces a position where the bishop on g7 becomes active.} 16. exd5 e4 17. 
Qe2 Rb8 {This is less convincing than 17... Qb4, but Black still retains good 
practical chances.} ({Black achieves good play with} 17... Qb4 $1 18. Bc4 Qxb2 
19. Nc2 axb5 20. Rab1 Qf6 21. Rxb5 f4 {This line is mentioned in the theoretical 
section of the course - *line #39*.}) 18. Rab1 (18. Bc4 {The engines prefer this 
move, giving White some advantage. This is not entirely clear to me, but it is 
not theoretically that relevant. 17... Qb4 is our improvement earlier.}) Rb6 
{Magnus goes for the rook lift, a common idea in this line.} 19. Qe3 Rg6 20. Bc2 
{The black attack becomes very strong after this move, but it's very tough to 
defend this position. White has offside pieces on a3 and b1.} (20. bxa6 {This 
greedy looking move is probably best.} Qh4 21. a7 Bb7 22. Bc4 Bd4 $1 {a nice 
tactical trick, that ensures the draw.} (22... Be5 23. g3 Qh3 24. f4 Bc7 {is 
also playable and avoids the immediate end of the game with the perpetual after 
22... Bd4. The engines already calculate a forced draw from here, which is of 
course rather academical and not very relevant for human play. White has many 
ways to go wrong in the defense.}) 23. Qxd4 Rxg2+ $10) Qh4 {The game is a mess. 
Black has given away the queenside, but still has huge chances on the other side 
of the board.} 21. b6 $2 (21. f4 $2 exf3 22. Qxf3 (22. Rxf3 $4 Bd4 $19) 22... 
Be5 23. h3 Rg3 $40) (21. g3 {This is the toughest defence.} Qh3 22. f4 {White 
needs to be able to defend on the second rank.} h5 {and Black's attack is still 
very dangerous. Instead of 22... h5 the move 22... Bd4 draws already for Black, 
which makes the whole line additionally unattractive for White: Black has a draw 
in hand and can look for more...}) Kh8 {Magnus already had a winning shot, but 
misses it.} (21... f4 $1 22. Qxe4 Rh6 23. h3 (23. Rfd1 f5 24. Qf3 Qxh2+ 25. Kf1 
Re8 {and White is in a mating net.}) 23... Qg5 24. d6 (24. Kh2 Be5 25. Qf3 Bg4 
{and this clearly is too much to handle.}) 24... Rxh3 25. b7 f3 {and again Black 
wins.}) 22. Nc4 $2 ({Again} 22. g3 {had to be played, with still sufficient 
chances to defend.}) Rg8 {This is good enough to win.} (22... f4 23. Qxe4 Rh6 
{The same attacking pattern would have worked again, as on move 21.}) 23. g3 Qh3 
24. Rfd1 (24. Qd2 f4 $1 {White collapses on h2 now.} 25. Bxe4 (25. Qxf4 Rh6 $19) 
25... Rh6 $19) Rh6 25. Qf4 Bf6 (25... a5 {A very strong alternative, getting 
...Ba6 on the map. This move was winning as well.} 26. d6 Ba6 27. b3 e3 {A cool 
winning shot!} 28. Qxe3 Bb7 {And Black wins.}) 26. Ne5 (26. b7 $1 {White would 
have posed more problems with 26. b7.} Bxb7 27. Nd6 Rxg3+ {This does the job, 
but the more obvious 27... Qxh2+ is not enough, surprisingly.} 28. Qxg3 (28. 
fxg3 Qxh2+ 29. Kf1 Qh1+ 30. Ke2 Rh2+ 31. Ke3 Qg2 {and Black wins! This is not at 
all easy to see!} 32. Nxf7+ Kg7 33. Ne5 Qxc2 34. Qxf5 Bc8 35. Qf4 Qc5+ 36. Rd4 
Rh5 {Ultimately White's king will fall.}) 28... Rg6 29. Nxb7 Be5 30. Nd8 Bxg3 
31. fxg3 f4 {And the attack crashes through.}) Bxe5 27. Qxe5+ f6 28. Qf4 Rg4 29. 
Qc7 Rg8 30. Re1 {Now Black wins quite easily.} (30. Qf4 a5 {The simple one. 
...Ba6 is decisive.} (30... Rh4 {This also wins, but requires to find an amazing 
string of moves.} 31. Qd6 Be6 $3 {A fantastic shot!} (31... Qxh2+ 32. Kf1 Qh1+ 
33. Ke2 Qf3+ 34. Kd2 Qxf2+ {This even lands Black in trouble.} 35. Kc3 Rh6 36. 
Rbc1 {and amazingly White is winning in this position! The king will be safe on 
the queenside and the d- and b-pawns are terribly strong.}) 32. Qxe6 (32. dxe6 
e3 {The key move of the attack.} 33. fxe3 Qxh2+ 34. Kf1 Qh1+ 35. Ke2 Qg2+ 36. 
Kd3 Rc8 $1 {This is the only move that wins!! The threat is now ...Qe4+, 
followed by ...Rh2+.} 37. gxh4 Qxc2+ 38. Kd4 Qe4#) 32... Rxg3+ 33. fxg3 Qxh2+ 
34. Kf1 Qh1+ 35. Ke2 Qf3+ 36. Kd2 Rh2+ 37. Kc1 Qe3+ 38. Rd2 Qxd2#)) Qxh2+ 31. 
Kf1 Qh1+ 32. Ke2 Qf3+ 33. Kd2 Qxf2+ 34. Kd1 f4 35. Qc3 fxg3 36. Bxe4 Bg4+ 37. 
Kc1 Rc8 {A good example of the type of attack that Black often manages to start 
in the Sveshnikov main line with 11. Bd3.} 0-1

